Step 1:

If Adrien's salary was 30% higher than Lylah's, and he was earning $40000 four years ago, then Lylah's salary four years ago was:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{40000}{1 + 0.3} = \frac{40000}{1.3} = 30769.23 \text{ (Lylah's salary)}
\end{equation*}
$$

Step 2:

Four years later, Adrien's salary increased by 40%, so his new salary is:

$$
\begin{equation*}
40000 + (40000 \times \frac{40}{100}) = 40000 + 16000 = 56000 \text{ (Adrien's new salary)}
\end{equation*}
$$

Step 3:

Since both salaries increased simultaneously, Lylah's salary four years later is:

$$
\begin{equation*}
30769.23 + (30769.23 \times \frac{40}{100}) = 30769.23 + 12307.76 = 43077 \text{ (Lylah's new salary)}
\end{equation*}
$$

Step 4:

The total salary the two were earning four years later is:

$$
\begin{equation*}
56000 + 43077 = \boxed{99077} \text{ (Total salary)}
\end{equation*}
$$

